Therefore, to have 1/x1 >=2a/x1, we need 1>=2a, so a<=1/2. But 1/2 <4/7, so even if we set a=4/7, the inequality would still hold here because RHS is 2a/x1 +3a/x2. Since x1 is approaching 0, x2 is fixed, so 3a/x2 is negligible compared to 2a/x1. Therefore, LHS=1/x1 +1/(x2 -x1)=1/x1 +1/x2 (since x1 approaches 0). So LHS ~1/x1, RHS ~2a/x1. Therefore, 1/x1 >=2a/x1 =>1>=2a. But a=4/7, so 2a=8/7>1. Therefore, the inequality would fail here. Wait, this is a problem. Wait, if we take t approaching 0, then x1 approaches 0, so x2 is fixed. Then, LHS=1/x1 +1/(x2 -x1)≈1/x1 +1/x2. RHS=4/7*(2/x1 +3/x2)=8/(7x1) +12/(7x2). Then, the inequality becomes 1/x1 +1/x2 >=8/(7x1) +12/(7x2). Rearranged, (1 -8/7)/x1 + (1 -12/7)/x2 >=0 => (-1/7)/x1 + (-5/7)/x2 >=0. But since x1 and x2 are positive, this is equivalent to -1/(7x1) -5/(7x2) >=0, which is false. Therefore, the inequality fails in this case. Therefore, our previous conclusion that a=4/7 works is incorrect. Wait, this is a contradiction.
